            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Half-life basics</h2>
              <p>
                Half-life is the time it takes for a quantity that decays
                exponentially to fall to half of its initial value. It is widely
                used in:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Radioactive decay</strong> (e.g. I-131, C-14, U-238)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Drug elimination</strong> and pharmacokinetics</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Biological decay</strong> (e.g. clearance of
                  biomarkers)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Any exponential decay</strong> process in physics,
                  chemistry, or engineering
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Core formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Exponential decay law</p>
                <p>\( N(t) = N_0 \, e^{-\lambda t} \)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(N_0\): initial amount</li>
                  <li>\(N(t)\): amount after time \(t\)</li>
                  <li>\(\lambda\): decay constant</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-2 mb-1">
                  Relation between half-life and decay constant
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( T_{1/2} = \dfrac{\ln 2}{\lambda} \quad\Rightarrow\quad
                  \lambda = \dfrac{\ln 2}{T_{1/2}} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>1. Remaining amount after time t</h3>
              <p>Using the half-life directly:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( N(t) = N_0 \left(\dfrac{1}{2}\right)^{t / T_{1/2}} \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                <strong>Example.</strong> A 100&nbsp;mg sample with half-life
                5&nbsp;days. How much remains after 10&nbsp;days?
              </p>
              <p>
                \( t / T_{1/2} = 10 / 5 = 2 \) half-lives, so \( N(10) = 100
                \times (1/2)^2 = 25 \,\text{mg} \).
              </p>

              <h3>2. Time to decay from N₀ to N</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( t = T_{1/2} \dfrac{\ln(N_0 / N)}{\ln 2} \)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Half-life from two measurements</h3>
              <p>If you know \(N_0\), \(N\), and the elapsed time \(t\):</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( T_{1/2} = \dfrac{t}{\log_2(N_0 / N)} = \dfrac{t \, \ln
                  2}{\ln(N_0 / N)} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Interpreting the number of half-lives</h2>
              <p>The number of half-lives elapsed is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\( n = \dfrac{t}{T_{1/2}} \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                After \(n\) half-lives, the remaining fraction is \( (1/2)^n \).
              </p>

