              <h2>Common use cases</h2>
              <h3>Radioactive decay</h3>
              <p>
                For a radionuclide with known half-life, you can estimate how
                much activity or mass remains after a given time, or how long it
                takes to decay below a safety threshold.
              </p>

              <h3>Drug half-life (pharmacokinetics)</h3>
              <p>
                Many drugs follow first-order elimination. If a drug has a
                half-life of 8&nbsp;hours, after 24&nbsp;hours (3 half-lives)
                only \( (1/2)^3 = 1/8 \) of the original amount remains.
              </p>
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                This calculator is for educational purposes only and does not
                replace professional medical or radiation-safety advice.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Is half-life the same as mean lifetime?</h3>
              <p>
                No. For exponential decay, the mean lifetime is \( \tau =
                1/\lambda \), while the half-life is \( T_{1/2} = \tau \ln 2 \).
                They are proportional but not identical.
              </p>

              <h3>Can half-life change?</h3>
              <p>
                For radioactive nuclei, half-life is effectively constant. For
                drugs and biological systems, the “effective” half-life can
                change with dose, organ function, or interactions.
              </p>
